Finemang gaffeln på b5 kvarstår. Siktar sedan mot c7 och gafflar svarts K och T. Parerar han med D på a6 så har jag L på f1 som slår hårt. Slår han min bonde a2 så gafflar jag ändå på c7 och tar hans T.

I think my improvement in this game was 12. Re1. I'm still not sure how I figured that out. Reviewing the game I was surprised when I saw what I had done. It's definitely encouraged me to think more unorthodox.
A positional player ?

As black I don't have an opening-repertoire.. The only opening I'm used to use is a sort of Pirc-Modern Defense.. Please correct me if I'm wrong!
The main idea in this opening-line is to control the center indirectly. You create a space for your king's-bishop and afterwards your plan is to attack the center.
According to me my opponent likes pretty closed games (most 1.d4-players do). By moving up his c-pawn 2 moves he's aiming directly for the center. Now he has control over my 5th rank.
Developing move..
According to Fritz we're playing a sort of Kings Indian..
Making space for my bishop and indirectly attacking e5 and c5.
Nice developing towards the center.
My idea was to play e5 within a few moves.. Mostly I play 4. Nf6 but after a few losses I'm trying something else..
White is building up a nice pressure towards d5 !

Leaving the choice to white.. Taking on e5 would result in an open game while d5 would close the gates and make it a closed game. I was aiming for the latter simply because closed games are more "my" style of playing.
A "closed" game it will be ! In meanwhile my opponent's f-knight is pretty inactive..
Preparing to castle..
"c5 is mine not yours" was white's way of thinking !
Preparation of playing a5.. My purpose is distracting that b-pawn so c5 would be all mine..
Developing his light-squared-bishop and preparing to castle kingside. Activating this bishop could go via his kingside or through a4 which would cost him a couple of moves.

Aiming for that b-pawn.. In a way I wanted to gain control of c5. If white played 9. bxa5 I would have a nice spot for my knight on c5 and having an open file for my rook! If white would move up his b-pawn one square I would have the same result.
Gives a closed position (looking to the pawns) but in this case it was the best move in my opinion.
Home sweet home ! In meanwhile e4 is attacked twice so White Player should do something about that !
The best move to play in my opinion. If 10. Bd3 then 10. ... Nfxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 and black was up a pawn.

I've been thinking long time on this move.. I know this seems a strange move but I was aiming for some activity on my kingside. Castling would result in a direct kingside-attack from my opponent. My queenside is pretty closed so the actions would be best on kingside..

Ok the cards are dealt.. Now it's time to come up with a good plan ! I spent pretty much time here.. 
Most people gave me this advice: it's better to loose because of time-trouble but with a GOOD position and a GOOD plan than to loose with a lousy position and hours on your clock. The only thing you need to learn in the first-mentioned example is finding a way to think/analyse faster..
The idea behind this move was to open up my f-file. For example; Ne8 f5 and white has trouble in defending e4..

Is he planning to exchange his "good" bishop against my strong knight ? Actually he would help me with exchanging.. Simply by Nf-d7 I could protect my c5-stronghold and in meanwhile making way for my f-pawn.. Maybe it would be better if he exchanged his f-knight by playing Nd2 --> Nb3 ?
Winning a tempo because it was my purpose to play f5 in a while..
There he is :) Preparation of f4 ?
My bishop was pretty inactive so it would be great to trade it for a nice white piece..
Defending his bishop. But after trading of those bishops it seems to me there's no nice field anymore for that knight.. So he'll have to retreat his Arabian Horse..
A good trade if you ask me..
Maybe 15. fxe3 would be another good move to gain some activity ?
g4 is a nice field for white's knight and/or bishop so it would be nice if I had that field under control..
He's making a shelter for his knight wich would help him covering f4 when he plans to play it..
Developing move.. The idea behind this move is to get a rook behind my f-pawn.
After this I suspect f4 will come ?
Again a double attack on e4 which stays double covered.. But with that covering 2 pieces are inactive..
As expected.. I won't catch it myself because white can double his rooks by playing 18. ... exf4  19. Rxf4 ... 20. Ra-f1
Putting some pressure on white's stronghold.. In meanwhile I'm making room for my a-rook..
Opening the whole position.
If white captures on d6 I would regain a nice spot for my knight on e5. And if white would play a blunder like Rf2 my queen could hunt his a-rook.. A pawn is the cost for it..
White wants to gain some material but (for now) he isn't able to get through my pawn-structure..
On this way the pawn-structure stays the same and is white's d-pawn still blocked..
I don't really understand this move.. Maybe it was better to play Rf2 followed by Ra-f1.
Knight on outposts ! Keeping busy his knight and queen..
Logical move..
A closed pawn-structure asks for knights.. So I want to keep my 2 knights and give my opponent 1 knight and 1 pretty inactive bishop for the time being..
Logical..
Preparation of f5.
Doubling his rooks. But for now he hasn't got an object of attack..

I played this move with a double purpose: 
1: if white slaughters my knight with his bishop I'll play hxg4 which creates an open h-line for my queen followed with a (possible) mate-threat.
2: if white doesn't capture my knight I'll play Ne3 which wins material (Nxc2). Note that white's queen isn't able to protect e3 !
The best move in my opinion.
Opening the h-file.. The doubled-pawn can be solved by playing f5..
Since e4 isn't attacked twice anymore the queen is free to go and even able to attack g4 !
Gaining a tempo to re-organise my troups. (like Ne5 wich defends g4 nicely)
Only possible move if he doesn't want to loose a rook..
Starting to build up pressure on h2 !
More active than Kg1 ! White is still in the possibility to play h3 sooner or later..
Covering g4 and attacking c4.
The queen is back in action ! Since my queen can't give mate at the moment I decided to trade queens.. White will loose a move while recapturing my queen wich gives me time to re-organise..
I'm up a pawn so it's time to trade some pieces..
Kf2 is also possible but would be followed by 30. ... Nd3+
Following my plan..
31. Nxf1 wouldn't be good since I would play 31. ... Nxc4
Opening lines !
I don't know for sure for this move.. Personally I felt more for Kg2 (making his h-rook active again).
Solving up my doubled pawn !
Probably with the thought of playing 34. Nd4 and 35. Nc6 ?
Again opening lines towards the enemy king !
One of the best moves.. 34. ... f3 would give me a passed pawn and 34. ... fxg3+ wouldn't be nice either !
Action !
Finally ! 35. Rf2 would result in 35. ... Rh-f8.
Catching pawns whenever it's possible !
Want to trade ? Offcourse !
According to our material we're even.. But still I like black's position.. His knight and rook are well-placed while white's pieces will need a few moves to regroup..
Only "good" move.. After this he's aiming for 38. Nd3 (attacking my knight twice).
I wanted to prevent the double-attack on e5 and also didn't want to leave my b- and d-pawns alone..
Relatively harmless as long my knights stays on e5..
Penetrating my enemy's back ranks..
Leaving alone his a-pawn ? Defending it will cost him the activity of his pieces !
40. Nc3 would be a serious blunder so it has to be 40. Nc1.
The only way to save his a-pawn.
Aiming for gaining some material (both b- and d-pawns can be attacked by Rc5 AND his knight is still in danger !)
White is totally pressed into defending..
A double-attack..
Only possibility.. He can't get to my king through the f-line and his h-pawn is (temporary) out of play..
Sure !

A serious blunder ! I noticed my opponent (a 82 year-old chess-player with a lot of experience) was getting tired of thinking and his nerves started to break in the endgame.. 
In my opinion it was his purpose to trade of our knights..
Ouch.. A safe move since Nxe5+ and Nc5+ would both result in respectively Rxe5 or Rxc5..
I guess he missed Rxe5 and hoped to win my rook if 44. ... dxe5 ?! would be played..

After this move my opponent instantly resigned.. 
I really like this game because it opened my eyes for some tactics positional play (remember the switching of my knights to c5 and e5 ?) gaining pawns ...
I hope you people also had some pleasure with watching this game ? Please let me know ! :)
Take care and enjoy your day !

Annotation for my Scotland Forever teammate.
e4 is a good choice for an opening move. Open games are easier to play and a better way to learn tactics.

Alekhine's defense - this was highly unusual when it first entered into master play in modern times it is a very rare choice in serious play- I think Lev Alburt was the last person to really use this as a main defense.

not the best choice. The f3 square is much better for a knight and the kingside pawn structure is broken up without any compensation. Consider challenging the knight by playing e5 forcing Black to waste time moving the Knight out of danger.
black has now transposed the opening favorably.

probablly not the ideal choice. White makes a 3rd pawn move in the opening. On the plus side white threatens to play d4 and exchange off the e5 pawn. However this doesn't solve where the g1 knight is going to go.
good white develops the bishop outside the pawn chain. However this move doesn't stop d5 from being played. 4... d5 5. exd5 cxd5 is with advantage for black.
while this restricts the diagonal white makes another pawn move in the opening and will find himself very far behind in development.
grabs space however I am not sure if it is superior to the straightforward 0-0.
while this opens spce for the bishop and knight white still neglects king safety and falls farther behind in being developed.
better here is simply Ne2 and then 0-0 to follow.
Black prepares d5.
Black grabs space in the center.
white is tempting fate with this many pawn moves and no king safety.
black should be thinking on how to open the center and get at the uncastled king.
white initiating the pin
this move is probably the beginning of the end as now White's king will have no safe haven.
black is clearly better here with a potential passed pawn and the bishop pair.
this probably helps white since it exchanges the bishop pair for no compensation and finishes white's development.
perhaps better was Nxe5 where white restores most of the material imbalance.
the exchange of rooks favors black who has 2 extra pawns and 2 passed pawns.

Här lämnar svart Scandinavian defence Lasker variation (B01). 6...Be7 hade varit i den linjen
Här tänkte jag först parera vits S med h3 men det är inte så bråttom med den paraden. Dessutom kan vit sätta min L på c4 i knipa genom att göra b5. Min L måste kunna retirera så draget blir därefter.
När jag slår hans S på d4 så kan vi hoppas på att han slår min S med D. Då slår jag med L på b5 och schackar. När han sedan säkrar K så kniper jag D.
OK då kör jag med ett mothot på f7 mot hans T.
Sätter min D i spel och öppnar upp för kombinationer. Slår han min S på c3 så slår jag hans T på a8. Säkrar han T så säkrar jag S.
Justja höll på att missa denna finfina gaffel tidigare. Men så länge man upptäcker möjligheterna i tid så är man på säker mark.
Han parerar smart så vi tar en bonde under tiden.
Avleder samtidigt L men sannolikt slår han min S på c6 och då slår jag med D på c6 och schackar.
Avledningen gick hem så jag tar hans D. Sedan slår han förmodligen mitt T med L.
Slår han S med T så går jag med D till c6+ och sedan tar jag hans L. Slår han S med K så säkrar jag f-T till d1+ efter K till c7 så säkrar jag S till e4.
Finemang han kunde motstå frestelsen att knipa mitt T. Då har jag en manöver som återger mig en hel del material från att schacka med D på c6.
Slår han S med K så slår jag bonden på c7 och kungsgafflar med T.
Här har jag lite bråttom för T till d1 hade skurit av svarts K bättre. Men jag spelar godkänt med D till c7+
Han kommer säkert att parera T med S till d7 men då kungsgafflar jag  på c6.
Som förväntat och jag har lite bråttom igen. Här hade S till d5 varit starkare eftersom det hade tvingat hans K att fly till f6 och blivit mer inträngd.
Materiellt tänkt men OK som drag.
Nu flyr svarts K till f6 iaf men jag är sugen på hans T. Spelar materiellt igen med S.
Här vinner jag mer tempo på att schacka med S på e4 så jag hejdar mitt materiella tänkande en stund.
Försöker han dubbelhota med K på f5 så går jag bara upp med D och schackar på e5. Det tränger honom längre in mot h-kanten.
Han viker undan så jag passar på att knipa hans L. Här är det befogat med en sådan manöver.
En rad alternativ står till buds men jag väljer att skära av diagonalen d8-h4.
Backar han eller går han till h5 ?
Han backar till h7 och skyddar samtidigt sitt T om han skulle vilja aktivera L. Här hade antagligen D till d3 varit bäst först och sedan S-manövern men jag valde S-manövern först.
Slår han med L så slår jag tillbaka med D. Går han upp med g5 så slår jag antingen med S mot f7 eller så säkrar jag L på e3.

Queen's pawn (D00) stonewall attack.
Här lämnar vit Queen's pawn (D00) stonewall attack där 5.Nc3 hade varit i den linjen.

Då börjar vi sabba hans "stenmur" av bönder även om han tillfälligt kan reparera den med exd4. I såfall fortsätter jag bara med dxc4 och knäcker upp en bräcka i mitten av muren. Går han då upp och slår Bxc4  så går jag upp med Nxd4 och då är min S säkrad av min D.
Sådärja nu är stenmuren spräckt och mitt läge i centrum ser bra ut.
Materiellt står vi förvisso lika men jag är betydligt mer utvecklad. Vits pjäser ligger långt bak och skräpar medan jag har en rockad inom räckhåll.
Här bryter han mot regeln att S bör utvecklas före L så jag ligger bättre till positionellt.
Här får jag en snygg gaffel mellan D och L även om den inte är särskilt stark.
Ett medelmåttigt drag men preventivt för eventuella attacker mot g5. Dessutom frikopplar draget min L på e7 så att den kan ägna sig åt mer offensiva uppdrag.
Blockerar vits S på b5 och d5 samt frikopplar min D från bevakningen av de rutorna.
Dags att flytta fram positionerna och spontant ser jag att mina bönder ligger långt bak. Får se upp med att inte låsa in damen bara.
Sätter lite press på hans D och luckrar upp hans försvar. Det börjar bli dags att närma sig hans K.

Det finns inga säkra kapt. så jag får tänka lite långsiktigt taktiskt. Eftersom han saknar löpare så kan det vara säkert att aktivera kungstornet. Sedan avtäcker jag e-filen med L och har den säkrad med T.
Här trodde jag att han skulle ta min D med T men desto bättre att han osäkrar bägge sina S.
Nu börjar min D bli mäktig och det är dags att se om det finns kombinationer som ger vit större materialförluster.
Här borde han ha tagit min L men trevligt med ett T gratis och jag tvingar även upp vits K längs h-filen.
Nu har jag både det materiella och positionella övertaget. Med så många bönder kvar så borde någon av dom kunna promoveras om vit är segmattad.
Här resignade vit alldeles för tidigt enligt min mening. Eftersom misstag alltid sker så hade jag väntat med att ge upp.

Bygger upp en annan offensiv istället och bibehåller pressen i mitten. Tabbar han sig så mattar jag på g2.
Ahhh ibland får man tacka gudarna :-). Nu får jag en snygg matt med Qxg2 !!
A Kings Gambit Tournament. Black turns the tables and wins quickly.
!? White intends to sacrifice the N for an attack.
Giving a pawn back for development.
Black has a good winning percentage from this position.
Black has good development White does not have much yet to show for the sacrificed piece.
?! castling into the attack.
! A strong counterattacking move. White's h pawn is threatened as well.
! White's King is now the target. The h pawn is threatened but even worse White's K is constricted.
Threatens mate and the White Bishop as well.
Trying for an escape but ...
drops the bishops leaving White 2 pcs behind.
? Leads to a forced mate but seeking complications.
Postpones the mate threat by checking.
! Black is not concerned about the rook since mate is threatened again.
Nor does Black care about taking the Bishop.
If only it were Whites turn to move but it is not.
Faced with mate in one White resigns.
Saved by miracle... or pity?

Here the correct pawn advance is g5 in order to prevent f6 because after gxf6 gxf6 Nd3 white has opened the black's kingside and with e3 can bring the queen into the attack. 
But I overlooked it.
the resulting position is similar but the black pawn structure is much better.

Next move the dsb is trapped. The only way to save it was h5 (h6 Bh4).
Moreover the d3 knight can be badly threatened by e4. Going to f4 means BxN exf4... leaving a damaged pawn structure. So I thought I had not time enough for h5. Obviously my position is inferior already.
I thought he would have taken with the pawn consolidating an impressive center. True this way he has pressure over f2.
Now if e4 the knight can retire to f2. It is not a wonderful choice but it seemed to me that I had to react even weakening my king (I hope I can castle queenside sooner or later).
Hmmm... in his shoes I would have gone on with the attack e5xf4. This move gives me a breath.
I want to take advantage of the uneasy black queen's position soon before he castles queenside and gives the rooks into the game.
Clearing the queenside castling and making him take care of what the hell is doing my queen up there :-)
Ah but this is not a good place for the knight. Just the only one!

Now I realize that the center pawns are going to advance. Bb4+ is there... C5 too. 
Just castling seems to be ok but d4 threats Qxa2... so the castling is not so wise as it seems. Let's contest a little his center advance.
You'll say I am not developing. Right. But this way if he plays d4 I can play Bc4. Passive moves as Be2 are nasty. I was hoping Bh3 would be useful but not yet.
He is seeking a sac in f4 Bxf4. Later.

The game starts with a series of sacrifices and white with a slight development advantage.
Both players want to capture the opposing rook with their bishops.
White threatens the queen while revealing the bishop looking to attack while the queen retreats...
...but the queen forces white to make a defensive move instead.
Black gains a tempo and material.
However the threat to the bishop results in a knight fork and black loses a rook.
White is very cramped. He decides to move the rook into play.
A clever move; the knight will be moved to reveal the check from behind. White must move his king out of the way.
White ahead in material offers a rook exchange. Black not wanting to retreat accepts.
A pointless check; it achieves nothing.
A much better knight fork.
Possibly the worst move available. It opens the door for the knight fork Nd5!+
The second pawn is now unstoppable. Faced with the prospect of two queens Black resigns.

The classical Symmetrical Defense of the Queen's Gambit Declined. Generally white plays 3. cxd5 and black should not reply 3. ... Qxd5. 4.Nf3 cxd4 5.Nc3 Qa5 6.Nxd4 or 5...Qd8 6.Qxd4 Qxd4 7.Nxd4 gives White a big lead in development. The full article at Wikipedia is here: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetrical_Defense
I've had some success with an early e3 even though it traps my dark squared Bishop for a bit
Fairly normal development through this point except 5. ... Bf5 which comes into play momentarily

This second move with the Bishop pins my Knight but I thought might be a slight loss of time. I'm not sure 6. ... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 is any better as white light squared Bishop is usually a good piece in this type of game. I thought Black should have placed the Bishop on this square with the initial move
This exchange gains back a bit of tempi for black
9. Qb3 does open the possibility of 9. ... Bxf3 10. gxf3 wrecking white's King side but the threat of 11. Bxf7+ or 11. Qxb7 both must be dealt with in the aftermath
This prevents the destruction of my Kingside defenses and places the Knight in a strong position one which is not as easily dislodged as might be imagined as 10. ... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Qxb7
Preventing 11. Bb5 pinning the Knight against the King although I was not really thinking about this because I didn't anticipate being able to prevent a shortside castle for black.
I thought this Knight was eventually doomed to exchange and decided to take the iniative and create doubled pawns for my opponent
This move seems to lock my Bishop to the c1 square to defend the b pawn for the foreseeable future

I imagine expecting 14. exd4 Qxd4 winning a pawn but I find a nice zwischenzug (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_between_move) move that really opened the game for me. I'm always happy to find such moves as I think they are often the sign of a stronger player.
I thought 14. ... Nd7 15. exd4 better for Black. Also possible is 14. ... Qd7 15. Qxd7 Nxd7 16. exd4
Here is my Knight sacrifice although it is for so short an interval before the recapture and gain of material I'm hesitant to call it a sacrifice
Taking the piece and essentially giving me the win. 15. ... Nd7 16. exd4 or 15. ... Qd7 16. Qxd7 Kxd7 17. exd4 both save the game although results in the loss of a pawn
The only move
This gives the King the f6 square for eventual escape otherwise my Bishop pair swoop in for a mate after Bxa6
21. ... Rxf8 22. Qxd7 picking up more material
Driving the Bishop off protection of the d1 square allowing my Rooks into the game
Removing more escape squares
Pinning the Knight from returning to the game but also threatening 25. Qd8#
Gaining the King an escape square at g6
Hoping for a pawn mate but it never worked out
Allowing Kg7 as an escape

28. Kd8 prolongs things again
I was happy with my play in this game. I saw a nice zwischenzug move and then set up a trap both of which allowed me to take control of the game.
I don't suppose this happens with actual physical pieces. This was a mouse slip. I intended to play d4.

This should reveal how narrow my book knowledge is. I'm going purely on whatever general precepts there are. Here I'm just trying to control as much of the center as possible. My opponent I imagine was suspicious of d3 and was playing it coy.
This is a terrible move any way you cut it. The game is won for me here.
This is a blitz game and I clearly didn't want to be skewered by the d pawn's advance. But Qe2 is surely stronger for me.
A very tempting move is an obvious blunder.

The Najdorf Sicilian again.

and White adopts the old-fashioned approach which I've been playing myself recently.  As others have commented the English Attack (featuring Be3 and f3) is now the main line.  Once again I shall refer extensively to John Nunn's book "The Complete Najdorf: 6 Bg5".

Although the Najdorf's 5...a6 is supposed to prepare the central thrust 6...e5 I've never seen it played against 6. Bg5 so I haven't tried it myself.  As it doesn't even appear in Nunn's book or in the later Nunn's Chess Openings (NCO) published in 1999 I think I'm probably right!  6... Nc6 would transpose to the Richter-Rauzer line.  Black adopts the more flexible Scheveningen formation.

Black's main alternatives at this point are the Polugaevsky Variation and The Poisoned Pawn: the Polu has an immediate 7...b5 which avoids putting the bishop on e7 where it often proves vulnerable.  Play becomes very double-edged and I have not had great success with it.  The Poisoned Pawn was once almost eradicated but has made a comeback and fills 112 pages in Nunn's book.  I recently lost as White against a 2000+ player here on Gameknot in that variation.  Interestingly enough some players have played 7...Qc7 against me here which also has a whole chapter to itself in Nunn's book.  I've carried on with 8. Qf3 which Nunn describes as the critical line.
Black's standard response to 8. Qf3

Immediate castling has been slightly unusual in my recent games.  White tends to play 9. Qg3 or 9. g4 or 9. Bd3 these days.  Looking it up in Nunn I find that 9. 0-0-0 was considered the main line by Nunn in 1996 when the book was published followed by one of those other moves.  Those lines take up 84 pages of closely packed analysis so we're in well-trodden territory.
Again the standard move.
This is one of three main alternatives to 10. g4 according to Nunn though he also discusses 4 other choices briefly.
The book response.
Again following Nunn.

and again :-)  Here Nunn mentions that Black has often provoked White into a strong sacrifice here with 11...b4.  I recently successfully played such a sac in the annotated game http://gameknot.com/annotate.pl?id=28675 though that was from a slightly different position and move order and against a weaker player than Burt.
This is the first departure from a main line.  Nunn gives two examples: a correspondence game from 1983 and an OTB game from 1990 but it doesn't feature in the later NCO.

I continue with my plan to exploit the half-open c-file and avoid castling into White's kingside attack.  The drawback of this approach is that White is also well placed to attack Black's Queenside castled position possibly with sacrifices on b5 d5 or e6.  Black has to be very careful.  White also has to resist temptation and not get carried away with sacrificial attacks that end in failure.
This leaves Nunn's two quoted games but transposes into a third (Mateu-Quiroga Buenos Aires 1995).

Now this takes us completely out of Nunn's book.  I recently lost another game (http://gameknot.com/annotate.pl?id=26547) in this sort of position when I didn't get my K off the c-file early enough.  In this position I have the added motivations of wanting to get off the White Q's diagonal h3-c8 and to make room for my R to come to c8 creating a battery on the half-open c-file.
This took me by surprise.  White adopts a cautious approach not committing anything to an irreversible attack but waiting for Black to make a mistake (a fairly sure bet from me!)
Black continues with his plan but how is he going to divert all White's defenders if White doesn't himself attack?
The bishop now eyes c5 b6 and a7: something else for Black to worry about.

Black attacks the Bd3 and defends the Be7 not that it was attacked at this point but could soon have been.  Both players had so many options around here that every aspect of the position and every move required meticulous consideration.  This move also permits White to play e5 if he wants when Black plans to play ...Nd5 inviting White to swap and clearing the way to c2.
White vacates the c-file preparing further defensive and attacking options.

I didn't want to tie my Q to the defence of the Be7 since I planned a line-opening ...d5 if conditions allowed.  Alternatively White might have planned f5 when this gave me the option of taking on f5 as well as responding with ...e5

White prepares to double on either e-file or d-file and also over-defends c2: a good flexible move.  While the rooks aren't coordinated there may be an opportunity to exploit so I now spent some time looking to see if I could get my Be7 to b4 before White could complete his rook manoeuvre.  However first I found it necessary to practice a little prophylaxis on the kingside.  I didn't want White to gobble up my unprotected pawns with an easily won end-game while I engaged in speculative adventures on the queenside.
Now my Nf6 may move.
Another waiting move from White.
With heart in mouth I commit myself to a central thrust which works remarkably well.
Now my opponent looked rather uneasy :-)
and even more so now...
Sensibly he recentralised his Q threatening mate in 1
Fortunately the defensive response is also aggressive.
White completes his rook alignment enabling him to swap on b4 if he so wishes.

As there's no longer a risk of the e-file being opened this rook was free to move to a more active square.  I did however have to be careful to avoid a mass swap off on d8 unless it was safe.  Given White's response perhaps it would have been better to take on a3.  White could also have swapped Qs and forced this R to move again with 25. Qb6+ Qxb6 26. Bxb6.
Unexpected and good.
? I thought this was my first serious mistake as now White could have won a pawn with 26. Qb6+ but White's response was even nastier.
! White threatened penetration on the White squares supported by Nxa5
I decided I had to swap off my beautiful bishop for his evil knight giving him doubled pawns into the bargain.
Played instantaneously.  I don't know whether he considered 27. Qb5+ or any other move at this point.
!?  Played as a deliberate provocation of the blunder to come.
??  I knew it was risky but I still did it as I thought my Q could dash back to defend on a7.  I should have looked this gift horse in the mouth and sent it back to the knacker's yard.

! The move I had missed.  I resigned because of 31...Rb8 32. Qa6+ Qa7 33. Qxa7++ or 32. Qc6+ Rb7 33. Qxb7++.  Will suggested afterwards that I might have grovelled for a while longer with 31.... Qa7 32. Rxa7+ Kxa7 with the hope of queening the e-pawn; but he soon found a way to prevent that.
The most popular opening of the day. Black has to accept: to do otherwise would be ungentlemanly!
The Muzio Gambit. White sacrifices a piece for the attack.
Black takes the Bishop instead of the Knight.
White must press his attack.
White regains the pawn.
Yet another sacrifice and Anderssen accepts.
White is closing in. If Black can hold out his material advantage will be decisive.
Yet another sacrifice and this one finally breaks the back of Black's defensive position.
Now the hunt is on...
Forcing Black to give up his Queen.
Now it is White with the material edge. The inevitable happens...
...and Black resigns. A splendid attack by Zuckertort.

Standardsvaret i French attack men fortfarande till vits fördel.
Här är det nog bäst att backa hem med S och standardsvaret i Petrov (C42) French attack är också mycket lämpligt 5.Nf6.

Här lämnar vit standardlinjen för Petrov (C42) French attack där 7.Bg5 hade varit i den linjen.
Säkrar g5 mot framtida attacker.
Normal utveckling och vi har sk "italienska löpare". Bra för min D som kan säkra sig i sidled om vit attackerar med S och L mot c7.
Spelar aktivt och undviker att backa ner med S. Här skapas åtminstone lite framtida utväxlingar.
Snabba utväxlingar men i längden är det bättre att röja undan hoten. Risken finns annars att vit kan mobilisera kombinationer med S L och D.
Slår med D för att komma igång med lite kombinationer. Vits S kan förvisso hota på b5 men då behåller jag skyddet mot c2 och schackar på e5.

Ser en kombination som kan ge mig hans L. Börjar med att schacka efter hans parering med S går jag med D till f4. Parerar han istället med L så förlorar han tempo av att gå jo-jo med L. Då går jag med T till e5.
Då får vi se vad han gör.
Han sabbar sin rockadmöjlighet vilket var lite oväntat. Då blockar jag b5 i händelse av att han vill tracka min  D med S.
Bäst att spela defensivt -men aktivt- och säkra L med T på e5.

Föredrar oftast ett offensivt spel så jag vinner hellre tempo genom att avancera och utväxla S. En mer positionell spelare hade omgrupperat S genom att backa till d7 och sedan gått vidare till c5. Det tar för lång tid och kräver mer positionell rutin än den jag har.
Nu har jag en snygg kungsgaffel på d7 mellan K och hans D samt L på b3. Sådana tillfällen ska man alltid utnyttja.
En livsfarlig gaffel för vit och det blir nästan tråkigt enkelt att matta honom.

Slår jag med T mot hans på e1 så är matten definitiv. Min D på d6 täcker flyktrutan h2 och det är godnatt för vit. Mer utmanande är att vänta med matten och knipa hans D istället för att samtidigt få lite rutin på dammanövrer.
Mattläget kvarstår ännu och slår han min S med g-bonden så slår jag hans T på e1 och mattar. Undviker att matta för spänningens skull och schackar med D på g6 istället.
Sådärja nu har jag endast materiellt övertag. Positionellt står vit i potentiell remikapacitet. Det ska bli intressant att öva på dammanövrer nu.
Vit har två T kvar och det gör honom hyfsat farlig. Dessutom står mitt T så illa till att en utväxling är klart motiverad.
Vit har ett T kvar en S och en L samt sex bönder. Farligast är hans L som har direkt diagonal mot min K så vi utväxlar L på c2. Hoppas han inte går till c4.
Skönt att han nappade på  den utväxlingen.
Backar hem. och laddar om för en ny attack.
Behåller initiativet genom att schacka och behåller även tempot.
Nu hinner jag aktivera mitt T och samtidigt blockera d-filen.
Han lämnar skyddet av sin S så vi går ner med D till c1 och stressar.
OK han försvarar S men hans bonde på a4 står en prise.
Här gillar jag inte idén av att ge hans S manöverutrymme genom att slå axb5 utan jag bypassar till a5. Sedan kan jag blockera hans b-bonde med min dito.
Han skapar stress genom att avancera sina bönder men jag har en gaffel med min D på b2. Detta låser vit till att försvara damflygeln statiskt medan han måste agera dynamiskt på kungsflygeln.
Nu hinner jag blockera b5 innan han blir farlig som promobonde.
Gafflar han med S på a4 så slår jag b-bonden med D.
Han stressar fram fler bönder och stormar lite på min planhalva. Blockerar direkt så jag slipper tänka på dom.
Nu blockerar han sin K och det kan utnyttjas med D.
Hotar f5 och han kan inte parera med T p g a dubbla bönder.
Han försvarar f5 med K men det gör honom bara mer inträngd.
Försvarar han med S till d1 så schackar jag på h5. Det gör jag i vilket fall som helst för nu är hans K avskuren från att backa hem.
Då sckackar vi och sedan ryker hans T.
Nu är vit bekvämt inträngd på h-filen och han kan endast agera desperat i försvar.
Min f-bonde står förnämligt placerad och tillsammans med D så kan vi knocka vits K i nästa drag.
Den här gången får han ingen frist utan nu sätter vi in nådastöten

I was dissapointed in the fact that I might have reached a draw despite my clear advantage but I wasn't about to give up. All the other boards were finished the score  2-2 and this game would decide the league champion. We needed a win.
From this point on the notation is only approximate. I was running low on time.
I was too dumb to notice on two occasions that I could have promoted this turn. Maybe he went to f1 that first time.
Note that just because a pawn is on the 7th protected by a bishop doesn't mean it'll promote. White's king is free to roam about the e2 f1 and g2 squares.
This was that 2nd dumb occasion. White's bishop would have to oscillate between a6 and b5 or my king would get to e2 and I would promote. Neither of us realized it though.
Seeing as this apparently failed I decided to go back.
And then I found the move...

If I would have taken the a pawn the position would be hopelessly drawn. Although I was at first skeptical about this move I finally realized its importance. White must now take the pawn on b5 or face a deadly threat of promotion but afterward the a6 pawn will recapture and be saved. Black's position is clearly won.

White resigns with less than 3 minutes on the clock for both of us. This was truly a long and exciting game. With this win Kamiak won the WESCO league by a single point* and for the first time ever. I hope you enjoyed viewing this as much as I enjoyed sharing it.

*It was actually 1.5 points since Stanwood had to make up a match against Monroe for which we expected them to win 5-0 (no offence to Monroe) but instead they went 4.5-0.5.

Pawn's crucial - they can not go back. So the white will need to put extra attention to this pawn.
It is obvious now that the black pawns are dominant in the center of the board and that the white pawn on e5 is more difficulty for the white than for the black.
That won't do it. The only way to support the e5 pawn is from f4.
Now it becomes obvious - the black pawns on d4 and c4 control the center.
Not Bxg5 - it will give the white strong attack in the King's wing.
The weakest point in the black's position is the pawn on f7 - so I have to pay the price of not playing f6 much earlier in the game; unfortunately that maneuver became impossible.
Again not Bxh6 - the same reason as before. After Qxh6 and Kg5 the white has huge advantage.
Although it seems bad for the black the white has nothing on the King's side attack. - Why? - you will see.
The only way to defend g4 - well no but I was still not in the mood to take the queen in defense. Yet Qd1 would have been better solution.

Due to the position of the e5 pawn the white has just limited range moves. He has to defend it with two figures - one is the queen but the other is either the knight or the rook. The black control of the center and the white pawns position does not allow the knight to get to any better square and the rook can not come to the third row in order to assist the white's attack and with the neutralization of the g4 possibility the white's King side attack came to a stop.
So now its time for the black to open the Queens side. Actually this is why I wanted the queen in the attacking position and not in the defending - I will have to admit that I was wrong.

As said before the opening should be in the Queen's side - not the middle. dxc4 opens the game for the white and places the black in not so good position. Furthermore the black d-pawn has open way to promotion.
The previous move have just made a possibility of coordinated attack of the Queen the Rook and the Knight - but will there be time?
Admitting the mistake - better late than never. The queen will defend the King and control the center and the rook will go to the Queen's side attack.
Instead using three pieces to guard the crucial weak black squares (f7 f6 and c5) it is done with only the knight and the queen. So it is time to see what can be done on the Queen's side.

The only way for the white defend - it defends the weak b3 pawn with the rooks it stops the d-pawn advancement with the rook and holds the knight and queen back with the knight and queen attack. 

Also now it has the possibility for the attack on the King's side - but...

The only way for the black is to penetrate into the white's "ranks". The rook on the first row is perfect for attacking - rook change with check will allow the black into disruption of the King's side attack.
It doesn't matter - it still allows for the black to advance to the second row.
It will prove that the white should have hold onto his rook. The black's advanced d-pawn is much harder to control without a rook than with a rook in play.
Finally something I should have played in the opening moves. With this the white will have to concentrate on defense - not offense.
I find the following white moves quite not understandable - I strongly believe that he should have found better position for the knight improve the pawn structure and bring the King into play.
Who needs queen with advanced pawn! - Oh I forgot the white needs his queen in order to defend the promotion.

An interesting variation of the Sicilian.
Both sides concentrate on quick development.
Black castles removing his King from the white Queen's line of fire.
White completes his own development and commences trying to build up an attack.
With the Kings on opposite flanks both players push forward. It's now a matter of who gets there "fustest with the mostest."
White makes a sacrifice to open lines and generate a fast attack.
Bl;ack tries to break the attack with a counter-sacrifice.

At the time this game was played it was thought that Black stood well here. If White tries 18 BxR? the counter is 18...B-K3! Now White is in trouble i.e. 19 BxP? BxPch! or 19 B-Q4 BxB! 20 RxB QxRP with a violent attack.
Ostapenko has other ideas.
Forced. 18... P-N3 falls to 19 RxPch! RPxR 20 QxPch B-N2 21 B-Q4!
This sacrifice wins the game for White. Black could have resigned here but he didn't.

Black's position is hopeless. If he tries 20... QR-B1 White has 21 RxBch!! KxR 22 B-Q4ch! P-B3 23 Q-N5ch! and Black can resign. [23... K-R1 BxPch wins both Rooks. and 23...K-B2 24 QxPch K-K1 25 QxBch K-Q1 26 B-N6ch R-B2 27 QxPch K-K1 28 Q-K5ch doesn't help.]
If ...K-B1 22 RxPch forces mate.

Kills Black's mating threat. Black has no good options here. 23 ...RxPch falls to 24 BxR R-QB1 25 QxPch K-B1 26 Q-R8ch K-K2 27 B-N5ch K-Q2 28 QxRch!! and the Black Queen falls. 23 ...QxPch is helpless against 24 BxQ B-B4 25 B-Q4 RxBch 26 K-Q1 P-B3 27 QxBP!! and wins. Black's best move is 23 ...R-B4!! but even this is refuted by 24 BxPch! K-R1 25 B-B5ch K-N1 26 B-Q4 R-K4 27 BxR PxB 28 Q-R7ch K-B1 29 BxB PxB 30 Q-R8ch!! winning the Rook and leaving Black in a hopeless position as the ending is lost for him.
Chasing Black's King all over the board...
The hunt is merciless.
